Diagnosis . Easily distinguished from known congeners by shape of procursus ( Figs 212–213 ): very long distal part (i.e. part beyond attachment site of ventral spine), long and slender transparent process, small process between ventral spine and transparent process (similar in
H. minotaurinus
), and protruding spiny membrane distally on prolateral side. Females are difficult to distinguish externally from congeners; median pouch of uterus externus folded toward anteriorly producing distinctive duplicature of cuticle ( Figs 204 , 207, 210 , 220 ) that is usually visible in uncleared specimens; pair of lateral pouches of uterus externus usually with sclerotized external margins clearly visible in uncleared specimens ( Figs 203 , 206, 209 ).

PALPS. As in 
Figs 200–202
; coxa with low retrolateral bulge, trochanter barely protruding ventrally, femur with retrolateral dark line and prolateral stridulatory pick; palpal tarsal organ exposed (
Fig. 226
); procursus (
Figs 212–213
) with small ventral ‘knee’, with distinctively long distal element, long transparent process and long and straight ventral spine (
Fig. 234
), with small pointed process between ventral spine and transparent process, with hair-like distal processes (
Fig. 235
), on prolateral side with protruding spiny membrane (
Figs 237–238
), possibly with glandular pores (arrows in 
Fig. 239
); genital bulb (
Figs 216–219
) with distally widened ventral sclerite, embolar sclerite with small cone-shaped processes (
Fig. 240
); with distinct dorsal membranous process (
Fig. 217
).

LEGS. Femur 1 with single row of ~28 ventral spines (
Figs 242–243
); without curved hairs (many hairs miss- ing), few vertical hairs; retrolateral trichobothrium of tibia 1 at 4%; prolateral trichobothrium present on all leg tibiae; tarsi without distinct pseudosegments but with many small platelets (
Fig. 244
).

Female. In general similar to male (
Figs 196–197
) but without spines on legs and with capsulate palpal tarsal organ (
Fig. 227
). ALS as in male (
Fig. 225
). Tibia 
1 in
31 females
: 6.8–10.7 (mean 8.1).
